solutions.content:
Hello Everyone, thank you for reading in advance!

**Approach 1 (Catalan Number):**
We can find the number of BST’s by thinking in recursive manner for ease:

1. Choose 1 as root, no element present on left-subtree. N-1 elements present on the right subtree.

2. Choose 2 as root, 1 element present on the left-subtree. N-2 elements present on the right-subtree.

3. Similarly, Choose i as root, i-1 elements present on the left-subtree. N-i elements on the right-subtree.

Then, Total number of BST’s ***C(N) = C(0)C(N-1) + C(1)C(N-2) +………+ C(i-1)C(N-i) +………….+ C(N-1)C(0).***
where C(i) is the number of unique BST with i nodes.

which is: ![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/9da2e01b-2240-45bc-b3b3-04ae93111c69_1636336728.9467251.png)

This formula is also called as Nth-Catalan Number. And finding unique BST with n nodes is one of the applications of catalan numbers!

**Time Complexity:** O(N^2)

Below is the code for my approach:

```
class Solution {
public:
    int numTrees(int n) {
        vector<int>cat(n+1, 0);

        cat[0] = 1;
        cat[1] = 1;

        for(int i{2}; i<=n; ++i){

            for(int j{}; j<i; ++j){

                cat[i] += cat[j]*cat[i-j-1];
            }
        }

        return cat[n];
    }
};
```

**Approach 2 (Recursive DP):** 

1. My intuition is that if we have numbers from `1` to `N`, then we will make each `i` as root once, and then send the nodes `(1 to i-1)` to the` left subtree` and the nodes` (i+1 to N)` to the` right subtree.`

2.  Note that the unique subtree for nodes `(1 to X)` is same as unique subtrees for `(X+1 to 2X)`, i.e., if we have `X` number of nodes irrespective of their values then the unique BST for those nodes will be same no matter what value they holds. For eg: the nodes 3 4 5 will make same number of unique BST as the nodes with values 7 8 9 as the number of nodes is same.

3. So in our recursive solution, for a node `i` that will be root, then `numTrees(i-1)` will give answer for our `left subtree` for nodes `(1 to i-1)` and `numTrees(N-i)` will give answer for our right subtree for nodes `(i+1 to n)` because we will have `(N-i)` number of nodes in this range and we only care about the `number of nodes`.

4. And then the answer for our node i will be the product of answer of left subtree and answer of right subtree, i.e. , `numTrees(i-1) * numTrees(N-i)`.

5. We will store our precomputed answers in our dp vector so that no repeated call is made for same number.

**Time Complexity:** O(N^2)

Here is the code for my approach mentioned above:

```
class Solution {
public:

    int solve(int n, vector<int>&dp){
        if(n <= 1) return 1;
        if(dp[n] != -1) return dp[n];

        int res{};

        for(int i{1}; i<=n; ++i)
            res += solve(i-1, dp)*solve(n-i, dp);

        return dp[n] = res;
    }

    int numTrees(int n) {
        vector<int>dp(n+1, -1);
        return solve(n, dp);
    }
};
```

