![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/cglotr/image_1572783162.png)

`dp[n]` answers the question of "what is the number of configurations if I have `n` numbers".

The next important idea is that we don't care what is the structure of the trees in the _boxes_ that
I drew in the above example. What we care is how many numbers that are inside the _box_.

It's easy to answer that question since we can get it from `dp[n]`.

Notice that to calculate `dp[n]`, we need to know `dp[n - 1]`, `dp[n - 2]`, and so on until we reach
the base case which is `dp[0]` & `dp[1]`.

Notice the pattern, `dp[n] = d[n - 1] * dp[0] + ... + dp[0] * d[n - 1]`. Therefore, we can build the Dynamic
Programming (DP) table with bottom up fashion.

**Code**

```Java
class Solution {

    public int numTrees(int n) {
        if (n < 2) {
            return 1;
        }

        int[] dp = new int[n + 1];

        dp[0] = 1;
        dp[1] = 1;

        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
                dp[i] += dp[i - 1 - j] * dp[j];
            }
        }

        return dp[n];
    }

}

```

