solutions.content:
The **brute-force** solution will give **O(N^2)**

But if we notice the following fact:

F(i)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;0 x B(1) + 1 x B(2) + 2 x B(3) + 3 x B(4) + ... + (n - 2)B(n - 1) + (n - 1)B(n)
F(i+1) = 0 x B(n)   +  1 x B(1) + 2 x B(2) + 3 x B(3) + .................... + (n - 1)B(n - 1) 

F(i + 1) - F(i) = B(1) + B[2] + B[3] + ... + B[n - 1] - (n - 1)B[n]
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;= sum(B) - n x B[n]

Using this derived equation we can quickly calculate the next F based on the previous value, which is O(1). Finally we get the maximum by O(N).

```
class Solution {
    public int maxRotateFunction(int[] A) {
        if (A == null || A.length == 0) return 0;

        int current = 0, max = 0, sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < A.length; i++) {
            current += i * A[i];
            sum += A[i];
        }

        max = current;

        for (int i = A.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            current = current + sum - A.length * A[i];
            max = Math.max(max, current);
        }

        return max;
    }
}
```

