solutions.content:
Okay, quite frankly I am not sure how this problem can rank as "easy", provided you want to do it efficiently, since it requires the skills I found in [another problem](https://leetcode.com/problems/daily-temperatures/discuss/844524/) ranked as medium, plus some more.

Anyway, enough ranting and down to business; first of all I will store the length of both input vectors in `len1` and `len2` respectivelty, then create a vector `res` of length `== n1.size()` and prefill it with `-1`.

If the second input vector is empty, I can stop here, just returning `res`.

If not, I will create more support variables:
* an array `dp` of length `len2`;
* a stack `s`;
* an unordered_map `matches` that I will initialised mapping all the values in `n1` as keys (with a temporary value of `-1`).

Then comes the great loop through `len2`, from right to left, with the index `i`:
* first of all, I am assigning `n` the value of `n2[i]` update the value of `matches` if i know a key was previosly there (I will not brute-force it all storing unnecessary data);
* I will then keep popping from the stack as long as the stacked values are lesser than `n`;
* if the stack ends up empty, I will write `-1` in the matching `dp` cell (`dp[i]`);
* otherwise, I will write in it the current value of `s.top()`;
* finally, I will push the current value of `n` into `s`.

If you wonder why I do the last 4 steps, in its [sibling problem](https://leetcode.com/problems/daily-temperatures/discuss/844524/) I wrote more extensively about it, with a step-by-step approach.

Now, time to wrap up: with one last loop, I assign to each cell of `res` a value taken from `dp`, in the position pointed out by `matches` for the key `n1[i]`. Not the most immediate line of code I ever wrote, but it works just fine.

Finally, I just return `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> nextGreaterElement(vector<int>& n1, vector<int>& n2) {
        // support variables
        int len1 = n1.size(), len2 = n2.size();
        vector<int> res(len1, -1);
        if (!len2) return res;
        int dp[len2];
        stack<int> s;
        unordered_map<int, int> matches;
        // marking all the necessary keys in matches
        for (auto n: n1) matches[n] = -1;
        // going to populate both the dp table and
        for (int i = len2 - 1, n; i >= 0; i--) {
            n = n2[i];
            // updating matches if it is a necessary key for later
            if (matches.find(n) != end(matches)) {
                matches[n] = i;
            }
            // working with the stack to populate dp
            while (s.size() && s.top() <= n) s.pop();
            if (!s.size()) dp[i] = -1;
            else dp[i] = s.top();
            s.push(n);
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < len1; i++) {
            res[i] = dp[matches[n1[i]]];
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Like the other problem, I tried to have `s` as an array, moving `pos` to populate it (with `pos == -1` to denote an empty stack), to see if I gained performance, but that seems hardly the case.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> nextGreaterElement(vector<int>& n1, vector<int>& n2) {
        // support variables
        int len1 = n1.size(), len2 = n2.size();
        vector<int> res(len1, -1);
        if (!len2) return res;
        // dp array and stack replacement array; pos == -1 means empty stack
        int dp[len2], s[len2], pos = -1;
        unordered_map<int, int> matches;
        // marking all the necessary keys in matches
        for (auto n: n1) matches[n] = -1;
        // going to populate both the dp table and
        for (int i = len2 - 1, n; i >= 0; i--) {
            n = n2[i];
            // updating matches if it is a necessary key for later
            if (matches.find(n) != end(matches)) {
                matches[n] = i;
            }
            // working with the array to populate dp
            while (pos > -1 && s[pos] <= n) pos--;
            if (pos == -1) dp[i] = -1;
            else dp[i] = s[pos];
            s[++pos] = n;
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < len1; i++) {
            res[i] = dp[matches[n1[i]]];
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

