solutions.content:
**Approach 1: Using an unordered map for efficient searching** -
O(N^2) time in the worst case and O(N) space
Explanation: 
1. Map every element in nums2 array to its index for efficiently searching the position later.
2. Traverse through the nums1 array and for each element in nums1, find its position `pos` in nums2.
3. Run a loop from `pos+1` to `nums2.size()-1` and find out the next greater element for each `num` in nums1.

```
vector<int> nextGreaterElement(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
	int n = nums2.size();
	int m = nums1.size();
	vector<int>ans(m, -1);
	unordered_map<int, int>mp;
	for(int i = 0; i< n; i++){
		mp[nums2[i]] = i;
	}
	for(int i = 0; i< m; i++){
		int pos = mp[nums1[i]];
		if(pos==n-1) continue;
		for(int j = pos+1; j< n; j++){
			if(nums2[j] > nums1[i]){
				ans[i] = nums2[j];
				break;
			}
		}
	}
	return ans;
}
```
***Optimized approach***
**Approach 2: Using unordered map and stack to store the next greater element of each entry in the map** - O(N) time and O(N) space
Explanation: 
1. In the unordered map we store the first greater element which appears next to an element` el` in the `nums2` array. 
2. For those elements having no next greater element are simply skipped.
3. While traversing the nums1 array, we see if the element is present in the map `mp` or not. If not present then push back -1.
```
vector<int> nextGreaterElement(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        vector<int>ans;
        unordered_map<int, int>mp;
        stack<int>s;
        for(auto el: nums2){
            while(!s.empty() && s.top() < el){
                mp[s.top()] = el;
                s.pop();
            }
            s.push(el);
        }

        for(auto num: nums1){
            ans.push_back(mp.count(num) ? mp[num] : -1);
        }
        return ans;
    }
