solutions.content:
### Solution

The smallest subarray that has the same degree as the overall array will be the subarray that starts at the first occurrence of the most frequent number and ends at the last occurrence of the most frequent number.

A map is a natural way to store the count of each number and then we can use that to find the most frequent number.

But how do we deal with ties? Consider [1, 3, 1, 5, 5] for example. We count all the elements and find that both 1 and 5 appear twice. So how do we know which is better?

One way is to store the index of each number when we see it for the first time. Then as we're counting in our map, if a number's count equals the degree, we might need to update the size of our smallest subarray. How do we know if we need to update it? It's if the distance from our current number to its first appearance is less than the current smallest subarray.

And if a number exceeds the current degree, we certainly need to update our current smallest subarray.

```cpp
int findShortestSubArray(vector<int>& nums) {
  unordered_map<int, int> counts;
  unordered_map<int, int> first_ind;
  int leader = 0;
  int degree = 0;

  for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
    int n = nums[i];
    counts[n]++;

    if (counts[n] == 1) {
      first_ind[n] = i;
    }
    if (counts[n] == degree) {
      int curr_size = i - first_ind[n] + 1;
      if (curr_size < leader) leader = curr_size;
    }
    if (counts[n] > degree) {
      leader = i - first_ind[n] + 1;
      degree = counts[n];
    }
  }

  return leader;
}
```

